  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Life saving assistance to IDPs and Returnees in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Afghanistan is facing a widespread humanitarian crisis where humanitarian needs are fast growing, especially 
due to the increase of civilian casualties and displaced populations. In addition, the on-going conflict 
Afghanistan is also facing a dramatic increasing in returnees from Iran and Pakistan. By the end of 2016 the 
total number of IDPs had reached 652,000 while the total number of returnees from Pakistan reached 620,000 
individuals. According to the UN, over one million people are estimated to be on the move by the end of 2016 
internally and across the borders, significantly burdening already fragile humanitarian context in Afghanistan. 
On top of the raging conflict, threats against aid workers are escalating, cutting access to aid and services for 
many Afghans in highly insecure area.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IDPs and returnees</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In light of this, the overall objective of the project is to alleviate the human suffering of IDPs and Returnees. The 
specific objective of the project is that men, women and children in the target population (380 returnee or IDP 
families, 2,660 individuals) have increased access to dignifying shelter, food, water, winterisation and selected 
services</narrative>
  </description>
